J'ai aussi modifié le trou des barres avant pour permettre un meilleur guidage des tiges chromé de 270mm.
J'ai fait aussi bien le support gauche que droit.
Le réglage permet une latitude de ±2mm de réglage Z.

description.text:
V2.0: I updated the whole adapter. I changed to the correct flange focal distance of 30,1mm and updated all parts that the shift functionality is working now.

V1.0: This is a hard-core remix of the "Pentax 645 to Sony E mount" Tilt Shift Adapter. First of all, the Shift function is not working but for sure it will in my second version in the near future. My first goal was to shrink this adapter that I can use my Biometar 80mm/2.8 from Carl Zeiss from my Pentacon SIX TL on my Canon 5D mkII or III as a normal portrait lens. I found another project which was close to the Pentax remix but both of them are have Macro functionality and the focus range is fixed to infinity. My goal was to keep the normal focus range of this lens, that means the distance between camera body and mid format camera lens has to be 24mm. After assembling the parts, I was impressed about this old lens which works pretty nice attached to my 5D. Yes, I noticed during remixing that the shift couldn't work but important to me was more to tilting the lens because of adjusting and tilting the depth of field. This effect is quite nice for portraits. Of course you can add this to your images with Photoshop but to build your own Tilt-Adapter is much more fun.

This is a modification of my clips to hold an inexpensive 11" x 8.5" glass plate to the heated bed of a Replicator 2X -> http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1908836

These clips are designed to hold a 200mm x 300mm x 3mm borosilicate glass plate to the heated build plate of the Makerbot Replicator 2X.

Demo Video: https://youtu.be/LAVd1VNNC0Y

Using a glass plate from an inexpensive document frame worked well. But I find that after a particularly busy printing schedule, the untempered glass often cracks from the repeated heating and cooling. This was not totally unexpected.

I found an inexpensive borosilicate glass plates on Amazon, that was perfect for my needs.
(Link and search terms in comments)

The 300mm length allowed these clips to be designed so that they hold the plate firmly, while remaining completely outside the print area.

Like my earlier clips, these utilize the groove on the underside of the Replicator 2X's build plate to keep them in place.

You may need to adjust the size of the clips to fit your own borosilicate glass plate, so I have included the FreeCAD file.

I was sick of bad bed adhesion on my M3D Micro when trying to use ABS or even PLA. I did not like the heated bed options that were out there and created my own that minimized printing volume loss. Just a bit of height is lost for my proto in order to easily bring out wiring. I will be making another proto later that uses a sized piece of borosilicate glass to fit into the existing place of the plastic bed. I have integrated a temp. controller, silicone heaters and a power supply to drive both heaters and am later making a quick circuit to close a temperature loop using the temp. controller. My plan is to go solid state and implement a PWM current source to minimize power draw. The relay output from the temp. controller will work nicely as a command. title: Case for Raspberry Pi 2 Model B

description.text:
Case for Raspberry Pi 2 Model B.

Intended screws for attaching the board to the case are thread-forming screws PT K25, with nominal diameter of 2.5mm and length of 7mm.

This was a project to make a case for Raspberry Pi 2. It was meant to be optimised for injection moulding with simple 2-part moulding tool.
There were also some other requirements:

  • The board is connected to the case with thread-forming screws
  • Design for assembly and Simple assembly
  • It must withhold a static load of 20kg and deformation must be smaller than 1mm and must not touch the board at any point.
  • Mass less than 70g,
  • Cases must be able to stack on each other
  • Calculate all the joints
  • Analysis of injection moulding
  • Design of moulding tool

My design has some advantages. There is no visible line between two parts. I really like how I was able to hide the line between two parts on the inside of the case. Also the force applied to the top of the case is transmitted trough the ribs directly to the legs. It does not affect neither the board neither the bottom part. I was also able to use a snap fit and therefore make an assembly and disassembly quick and easy.

3d printed version is a little bit different. I had to make the top flat. I had to thicken some parts of the case (mostly ribs). I changed position of the slots on the bottom part, so you can route through a ribbon cable for camera.There were also some other minor changes to improve printability.
It can be printed without support material. There are some tricky bridges and some very thin parts, but I was able to print it without any problems.
You might need to file down or sand some parts to ensure a better fit. Mostly on the part of the case around USB connectors.

*You can't see it on the pictures, but there is supposed to be a 1mm gap between the case and the table, so it gets a little bit of air from the bottom and it also doesn't sit on ribbon cable.

Disclaimer: I do not guarantee that this case can withhold 20 kg of load or that deformation is less that 1mm.

description.text:
These GoPro protective cases are designed to be printed using PLA and not TPU. I'm almost certain that they will not work well in TPU format at all. So if you go down that path don't complain that one cable tie doesn't work or you're getting jello in the footage.

We've run these cases since the Aliens first came out and today we haven't damaged a GoPro, having said that I'm sure someone will hit a light post at 100mph and they'll manage to explode a GoPro.

There are 3 main types of Mounts here. A 30 degree and 35 degree tilted mounts that will work with almost any Alien Style Quad using one Zip Tie to hold it down. We also have a mount with Zero tilt and it's designed for the Helix. You'll notice on this one there is an access section for the MicroSD and Charge Cable which you can break away if desired. On the Helix this is the mount we use and once you cable tie it down, you can't access the the rear to remove the GoPro so hence the hatch for MicroSD Access and Charging.

The fourth part is the main face plate which will house the Lumenier lens and also take the main impact in a crash.

You will need to purchase Lumenier Layer Lenses since this is what this design is based around.

For those of you who are going to ask I've finally enabled Thingiverse Tipping.

Anyway I hope you find these files useful

title: Brooklyn Bridge bookend
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
I designed this myself. The only thing that was already made was the outline of the Brooklyn bridge. I found that image online, converted it to a SVG file and imported onto my tinkercad. Everything else I made myself: the bookends, the suspension cables. It took me hours to complete this design mostly because I am new to CAD software and also because I am a perfectionist. I would very much appreciate the likes and/or adding it to your collection. Thanks!

Unfortunately don't know when I'll have time to print this since I have so much stuff lined up to print. If someone prints it out before me, please post =)

UPDATE: Finished uploading the mirror image.

UPDATE: So there was a problem with the "suspension cables" since they are at an angle. As they print tension is created and don't stay put in their position. I tried printing the other side with a support to hold each suspension cable in its place but the end result was worse. If anyone can think of a solution, i would appreciate the help. Otherwise if you really want to print this and don't mind a little bit of gluing let me know and I can edit the stl so the suspension cables print out separate.

title: Malyan M150 Acrylic Bed Holder Clip

description.text:
After finding that my first print with the Malyan M150 stuck pretty badly to the sheet they provided I had to find another material to print on. I had some 2.2mm sheets of Acrylic laying around so I cut one to size, left the sheet on to kind of create a buffer between the metal and acrylic and made these clips to hold it in place along with binder clips.

I use the binder clips on the corners and use these clips at the front and the middle sections to straighten the acrylic. If you use binder clips at the front, the print head won't clear it where as these clips will just barely clear the print head.

They are easy to remove and re-insert, you may have to file them down a tiny bit but it depends on your setup.

description.text: Quick design in Solidworks; wanted a tennis keychain that was easily identifiable, and also light on materials, so I made this one.

Props to the night crew at the Danbury Hackerspace for this gross but fun project.

Parts for mounting a can of can cheese to an Inventables X-Carve CNC.
The set includes a servo mount, can mounting clamp, shim (for using frosting cans, they're slightly smaller), a fine tip nozzle for the cheese, and an arm to attach to the servo.

There are nut pockets in the servo block so you can assemble the clamp/block with two screws.

We connected the servo to an Arduino and used that to control the on/off dispensing arm. When a button was pushed or the switch was shorted, the arm would press the cheese nozzle and the food goo would extrude.

These layers are going to be gigantic - .5 cm or so. Figuring how to modify your gcode to make your favorite cheesy shapes is a fun part of the project. Figuring out the right height above the platform is also important. This project was from last winter, so I'll see what I can dig up an will update the files and notes accordingly.

description.text:
This is a simple sponge filter for breeding and larval tanks.
It requires two zip ties, a porous filtration sponge from your local fish store, some airline, and an air pump.
Assembly is pretty simple. Print this out, attach an airline, wrap the standpipe with the porous sponge and zip ties, and attach the air pump. Done.

For those of you unfamiliar with sponge filters, please see the following URL: http://www.jehmco.com/html/hydro-sponge_filters.html The scad file is attached in case there are changes that you'd like to make. Assembly photos are attached as well. Print and enjoy! Depending on your local fish store (LFS), you may be able to find cylindrical or block sponges with the appropriate diameter pre-made in them. If not, you can either get a flat sponge and zip tie it around the filter stand pipe or bore out a 20 mm hole in one yourself. Feedback is welcome on how to make this better for everyone.
